{
  "doc_id": "35703",
  "text": "Even after 6 years, the investigation of [CITATION_1] remains one of the rare examples where with the help of proteomics one protein (ESAT-6) was separated into eight protein species and four of them were analysed with 100% sequence coverage, allowing a real protein species differentiation and a correlation to different functions. Only the non-acetylated protein species were able to interact with CFP-10. This interaction is important for the transfer of ESAT-6 out of the bacterial cell. It may be speculated that in the secretome, which was analysed, the rebinding of ESAT-6 to CFP-10 should be avoided and, therefore, ESAT-6 is acetylated to fulfil its task without competition with the interaction to CFP-10.",
  "correct_citation": {
